Adem치s, mediante la informaci칩n extra칤da de la tabla ANOVA, se evidencia que la media de sueldos de empleados remotos es de $ 136481.5 y la media de sueldos de empleados de oficina es de $ 144316.2, lo que indica que los empleados que trabajan toda su jornada en oficina ganan $7834.7 mas al a침o que los empleados remotos. 3/9/2023, 21:10 - Emily Zavala Mi Amorcito 仇벒잺游눘: n our work, we have proposed a novel privacy-aware person search (PAPS) model with distributed architecture that performs ReID as well as reconstructs person images upon querying at the user-end, without the need to store or transmit images/videos. The proposed model consists of three dedicated sub-networks, i.e. ReID, encoder and decoder. Here, the ReID part of the model performs person search, whereas the encoder늓ecoder part reconstructs person images at the user-end. The objective of the encoder is to generate different (unique) features for different input images irrespective of person identity; whereas the objective of the ReID sub-network is to generate i) similar features for person images belonging to same identity, and (ii) dissimilar features for person images belonging to different identities. Therefore, the PAPS model has to be designed accordingly, and appropriate training strategies have to be employed to address the contradiction between ReID and the encoder sub-networks.

4/9/2023, 20:14 - Lexo: Before starting to create my elevator pitch, I was looking for some information o pillars to stand my hypothesis.

The main pillars are Industry and Agriculture, I have experience developing some projects back in Ecuador, mainly in IoT to recollect big data, and then translate it in graphs/information to help management for a better decision to the enterprise.

Both Agriculture and Industry are essential for supply chain worldwide, so attacking one of these topics will have a great impact on the statistical model.

In this thesis I will select Industry topics, and making some research about the main problems I can use two.

One of the topics is about how to predict the demand of the food industry based in a machine learning model using sales, economics conditions and seasons to improve the production planning.

The other topic is optimizing energetic resources to change to sustainable energies, how to use the energy demand, climatic/earth condition (satellites datasets) and consumption patterns to propose solar/Eolic projects in industries.

Tomorrow I will talk with professor Greg to choose the best one based on academic advisors and dataset.

7/9/2023, 21:01 - Lexo: ## 1. How many total games have the Cubs won and lost between 1876 and 2022?


In the homework we have three questions to answer showing some code and writing to explain:

1. How many total games have the Cubs won and lost between 1876 and 2022?

We have to sum the values from 1876 to 2022 (no filter in the years) using the columns W and L for Wins and Losses respectively.

```{r cubs}
Cubs_Wins = sum(cubs$W)
Cubs_Loses = sum(cubs$L)

print(Cubs_Wins)
print(Cubs_Loses)

```
## 2. What year did the Cubs score the most runs? What year did the Cubs score the fewest runs? Do you have any thoughts about the year that the Cubs scored the fewest runs?

For the next question we need to know how was the best (maximun value) and the worst (minimun value) of the runs during the years of the chicago cubs:

2. What year did the Cubs score the most runs? What year did the Cubs score the fewest runs? Do you have any thoughts about the year that the Cubs scored the fewest runs?

After we obtain the values we can make some observations of the seasons.


```{r cubs}
Cubs_Best_Runs = which.max(cubs$R)
Cubs_Worst_Runs = which.min(cubs$R)

print(cubs[Cubs_Best_Runs, "Year"])
print(cubs[Cubs_Worst_Runs, "Year"])

```
## 3. In how many seasons was the Cubs total attendance (i.e. the variable Attendance) over 3 million?

For the last questions we need to know how many seasons was the Cubs total attendance exceed 3 million, we can obtain the value with a iteration and conditioning each value to count the total quantity.

3. In how many seasons was the Cubs total attendance (i.e. the variable Attendance) over 3 million?

```{r cubs}

Cubs_Best_Runs = which.max(cubs$R)
Cubs_Worst_Runs = which.min(cubs$R)

print(cubs[Cubs_Best_Runs, "Year"])
print(cubs[Cubs_Worst_Runs, "Year"])

```

## R Markdown

When you click the **Knit** button a document will be generated that includes both content as well as the output of any embedded R code chunks within the document. You can embed an R code chunk like this:

```{r cubs}
cubs <- read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/gjm112/DSCI401/main/data/cubs_all_time.csv")
```

```{r cubs}
summary(cubs)
```

``

## 1. How many total games have the Cubs won and lost between 1876 and 2022?


In the homework we have three questions to answer showing some code and writing to explain:

1. How many total games have the Cubs won and lost between 1876 and 2022?

We have to sum the values from 1876 to 2022 (no filter in the years) using the columns W and L for Wins and Losses respectively.

```{r cubs}
Cubs_Wins = sum(cubs$W)
Cubs_Loses = sum(cubs$L)

print(Cubs_Wins)
print(Cubs_Loses)

```
## 2. What year did the Cubs score the most runs? What year did the Cubs score the fewest runs? Do you have any thoughts about the year that the Cubs scored the fewest runs?

For the next question we need to know how was the best (maximun value) and the worst (minimun value) of the runs during the years of the chicago cubs:

2. What year did the Cubs score the most runs? What year did the Cubs score the fewest runs? Do you have any thoughts about the year that the Cubs scored the fewest runs?

After we obtain the values we can make some observations of the seasons.

```{r cubs}

Cubs_Best_Runs = which.max(cubs$R)
Cubs_Worst_Runs = which.min(cubs$R)

print(cubs[Cubs_Best_Runs, "Year"])
print(cubs[Cubs_Worst_Runs, "Year"])

```

## 3. In how many seasons was the Cubs total attendance (i.e. the variable Attendance) over 3 million?

For the last questions we need to know how many seasons was the Cubs total attendance exceed 3 million, we can obtain the value with a iteration and conditioning each value to count the total quantity.

3. In how many seasons was the Cubs total attendance (i.e. the variable Attendance) over 3 million?


```{r cubs}
Season_num = 0

for (x in cubs$Attendance) {
  if (!is.na(x) & (x >= 3000000)){
    Season_num  <- Season_num + 1
  }
}

print(Season_num)


```

dim(pima)

# remove missing values

# add small perturbation

14/9/2023, 22:14 - Lexo: Code 3
14/9/2023, 22:14 - Lexo: # set working directory
setwd("C:/Users/mxi1/OneDrive - Loyola University Chicago/Loyola/STAT 408 Fall 2023")

# read data
pima <- read.csv('pima.csv')

# transfer test from character to factor
pima$test <- as.factor(pima$test)
summary(pima)

# correlation coefficient without missing values
cor(pima$insulin, pima$glucose, use='complete.obs')

# visualization
plot(insulin~glucose, data = pima)

# correlation in healthy group
pima.neg <- pima[pima$test=='negative',]
cor(pima.neg$insulin, pima.neg$glucose, use='complete.obs')
plot(insulin~glucose, data = pima.neg)

# correlation in diabetes group
pima.pos <- pima[pima$test=='positive',]
cor(pima.pos$insulin, pima.pos$glucose, use='complete.obs')
plot(insulin~glucose, data = pima.pos)

# compare diabetes pedigree function 
plot(diabetes ~ test, pima)

# two-sample t test 
t.test(pima.neg$diabetes, pima.pos$diabetes)

# simple linear regression with insulin as response and glucose as predictor
lm.model <- lm(insulin~glucose, data = pima)

# show lease square estimation
lm.model

# plot the fitted regression line in the scatter plot
plot(insulin~glucose, data = pima)
abline(lm.model,col='red', lwd=2)

# check goodness of fit and hypothesis test
summary(lm.model)

14/9/2023, 22:34 - Emily Zavala Mi Amorcito 仇벒잺游눘: H0: The mean strength of the sample is > 100 lb/in2 (As the exercise details that the pipe should exceed 100 lb/In2 to meet especifications)

Ha: The mean strength of the selected welds is 곣 100 lb/in2 (The alternative Hypothesis states that the mean of the sample doesn't meet the especifications of exceeding 100 lb/in2)

Therefore: 
H0: 풮>풮_0
Ha: 풮<풮_0

In case that the p-value is  less or equal to the Significance level, we would have enough statistic evidence to reject the null hypothesis, meaning that the mean of the sample does not meet the especifications.

Type I error: Null hypothesis is rejected but the mean strength of the sample is > 100 lb/in2, meaning that is true.

Type II error: Null hypothesis is not rejected but the mean strength of the sample is< 100 lb/in2 meaning that is false that the pipes selected have meet the requirements.

20/10/2023, 21:45 - Emily Zavala Mi Amorcito 仇벒잺游눘: # Load the ggplot2 library
library(ggplot2)

# Assuming you have a data frame named 'employee' with relevant columns 'Age', 'Gender', 'City', and 'Education'
cities <- unique(employee$City)

for (city in cities) {
  city_data <- subset(employee, City == city)
  
  # Create a facet grid to facet by Gender on the same row and Education on columns
  p <- ggplot(data = city_data, aes(x = Education, y = Age, fill = Gender)) +
    geom_boxplot() +
    labs(title = paste("Age vs. Gender by Education in", city),
         x = "Education Level",
         y = "Age") +
    theme_minimal()  # Customize the plot theme as needed
  
  print(p)
}

20/10/2023, 22:17 - Lexo: # Step (b): Compute average rides per day for each station on the red line
station_avg_daily_rides <- merged_data %>%
  group_by(STATION_NAME) %>%
  summarize(avg_rides_per_day = sum(rides) / n_distinct(date))

station_avg_daily_rides

# Compute average rides per day for each station for each month
station_avg_rides_per_month <- merged_data %>%
  mutate(month = month(Date)) %>%
  group_by(STATION_NAME, month) %>%
  summarize(avg_rides_per_month = sum(rides) / n_distinct(date))

station_avg_rides_per_month

# Step (c): Calculate the ratio for each station and month
station_avg_rides_per_month <- station_avg_rides_per_month %>%
  left_join(station_avg_daily_rides, by = "STATION_NAME") %>%
  mutate(ratio = avg_rides_per_month / avg_rides_per_day)

station_avg_rides_per_month

# Find and display the top ten largest ratios
top_10_ratios <- station_avg_rides_per_month %>%
  arrange(desc(ratio)) %>%
  head(10)

top_10_ratios

# Step (d): Compute the standard deviation of the ratio for each station
station_std_dev <- station_avg_rides_per_month %>%
  group_by(STATION_NAME) %>%
  summarize(std_dev = sd(ratio))

station_std_dev

# Find the stations with the 5 largest standard deviations

  arrange(desc(std_dev)) %>%
  head(5)

top_5_std_dev_stations

20/10/2023, 22:20 - Emily Zavala Mi Amorcito 仇벒잺游눘: I apologize for the confusion. It appears that there was an issue in the previous code, and it might be due to the structure of your data. If you don't have a 'Date' column in the `average_rides_per_month` and `average_rides_per_day` DataFrames, then you should use a different method to calculate the ratio. 

You can calculate the ratio without merging these DataFrames. Here's an updated code snippet that calculates the ratio directly from the DataFrames you have:

```python
# Assuming 'average_rides_per_month' and 'average_rides_per_day' are both DataFrames
# Make sure they both have 'STATION_NAME' as an index

# Calculate the ratio for each station and each month
merged_data = average_rides_per_month.copy()  # Create a copy of the 'average_rides_per_month' DataFrame
merged_data['ratio'] = merged_data['rides'] / average_rides_per_day['rides']

# Find the top ten largest ratios
top_10_ratios = merged_data.nlargest(10, 'ratio')

# Display the top ten largest ratios
print(top_10_ratios)
```

In this code, we directly calculate the ratio by dividing the 'rides' in the `average_rides_per_month` DataFrame by the 'rides' in the `average_rides_per_day` DataFrame. This avoids the need to merge DataFrames and should work regardless of the structure of your data.

  # Handle missing values if needed

}

# Convert 'ratio' to numeric

# Create the ggplot line plot
ggplot(top_5_stations_data, aes(x = month, y = ratio, color = STATION_NAME)) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(title = "Ratio of Rides per Month for Top 5 Stations with Largest Standard Deviations",
       x = "Month", y = "Ratio") +
  theme_minimal()

30/10/2023, 18:56 - Lexo: Have you, your family, or close friends or colleagues ever experienced harm or mistreatment or threats in the past by anyone?
30/10/2023, 18:56 - Lexo: puse yes
30/10/2023, 18:56 - Lexo: y respondi esto
30/10/2023, 18:56 - Lexo: Explain in detail (1) what happened; (2) when the harm or mistreatment of threats occurred; (3) who caused the harm or mistreatment or threats; and (4) why you believe the harm or mistreatment or threats occurred.
30/10/2023, 18:56 - Lexo: Since March 11, 2023, I have received calls from various numbers on my landline at home, threatening to harm me if I did not pay them thousands of dollars. I proceeded to block the numbers, as many took advantage of the country's situation to make extortion calls, pretending to be part of criminal gangs. I informed my family and supervisors at my workplace in Guayaquil, but I continued with my work responsibilities, ignoring the constant calls.

Among my responsibilities as the Sales Manager was to supervise that sales were conducted by visiting customers at their farms. During one of these visits to the Don Antonio farm on March 14, in the Rocafuerte Manabi area, a car with three men approached me. One of them approached me. window and explained that they were representatives of a land investor and-that they needed a proposal for a plant irrigation system for a project. These individuals provided me with a list of materials to quote, but they did not provide much information about their origin. However, they already had my business card. I was afraid, but I had to serve them as customers and provide the proposal they requested.

I proceeded to provide them with a quote over the phone the next day from my work phone, but I received no further response from them. Nevertheless, that same evening, I received calls from several different numbers on my home landline, claiming to be the gentlemen to whom I had quoted the previous day. They threatened to kidnap me if I did not give them $60,000, stating that they represented the criminal organization known as the "Chone killers" and that they are already knew where I worked and my work hours. I reported the situation to my immediate supervisor, and he authorized me to work temporarily from home.

My first thought was to file a police report and go into hiding. However, acquaintances with knowledge of criminal matters informed me that these individuals had managed to track even those who made anonymous reports and took serious reprisals. Furthermore, in many other cases, they did not proceed with extortion after being ignored. Therefore, I was advised not to report it, but I immediately requested the cancellation of my home landline.

For approximately a month and a half, I avoided going anywhere and worked remotely. Unfortunately, calls from extortionists continued to my work mobile phone, which I ignored as much as possible, until on May 3, I answered a number that was not identified as an extortion call. They told me they had waited too long and that I had exactly one week to give them the money, or they would kill me.

5/11/2023, 21:30 - Emily Zavala Mi Amorcito 仇벒잺游눘: After using regression-based imputation to fill in the missing values in the "galamiss" dataset and fitting the linear model, we have the following results:

Model fitted using regression-based imputation (linear_model_galamiss_reg):
- R-squared: 0.6503
- Adjusted R-squared: 0.5774
- Residual standard error: 74.52

Now, let's compare these results to the previous fits:

1. Model fitted using the deletion strategy for missing values (linear_model_galamiss_del):
   - R-squared: 0.7668
   - Adjusted R-squared: 0.702
   - Residual standard error: 67.36

2. Model fitted to the complete "gala" dataset (linear_model_gala):
   - R-squared: 0.7658
   - Adjusted R-squared: 0.7171
   - Residual standard error: 60.98

Comparing these models:

- The model with regression-based imputation (linear_model_galamiss_reg) has the lowest R-squared (0.6503) and the highest residual standard error (74.52) among the three models. This suggests that imputing missing values using regression might have introduced more uncertainty and reduced the model's predictive power.

- The model with missing values deleted (linear_model_galamiss_del) had the highest R-squared (0.7668) but also a relatively high residual standard error (67.36).

- The model fitted to the complete "gala" dataset (linear_model_gala) had an R-squared of 0.7658 and the lowest residual standard error (60.98), indicating a relatively better fit compared to the imputed models.

In conclusion, while imputing missing values using regression can be useful for retaining the sample size and utilizing available information, in this case, the models fitted to complete data or with missing values deleted seem to provide a better fit with higher R-squared and lower residual standard errors. The imputation process may introduce additional uncertainty, leading to a less accurate model. The choice between these approaches should consider the trade-offs between data completeness and model performance.

import plotly.express as px
from macleish import whately

# Convertir la serie temporal a un DataFrame
df = pd.DataFrame({'date': whately.index, 'temperature': whately.values})

# Agrupar por d칤a y calcular min, max y promedio de temperatura para cada d칤a
daily_temps = df.resample('D', on='date').agg({'temperature': ['min', 'max', 'mean']}).reset_index()

# Crear un gr치fico interactivo con Plotly
fig = px.line(daily_temps, x='date', y=['temperature_min', 'temperature_mean', 'temperature_max'],
              labels={'value': 'Temperature (춿C)', 'date': 'Date'},
              title='Whately 2015 Daily Temperature',
              line_shape='linear', render_mode='svg')

# Mostrar el gr치fico
fig.show()

The Plotly Express code references these new column names in the y parameter of the px.line function.
This should create an interactive plot with three lines, each representing the daily minimum, maximum, and mean temperatures. Please give it a try and let me know if it works for you.

whately$when <- as.Date(whately$when)

datos_diarios <- whately %>%
  group_by(when) %>%
  summarize(Temperature_Max = max(temperature),
            Temperature_Min = min(temperature),
            Temperature_Avg = mean(temperature))

grafico_interactivo <- plot_ly(datos_diarios, x = ~when) %>%
  add_lines(y = ~Temperature_Max, name = " Max", line = list(color = "red")) %>%
  add_lines(y = ~Temperature_Min, name = " Min", line = list(color = "green")) %>%
  add_lines(y = ~Temperature_Avg, name = " Avg", line = list(color = "blue")) %>%
  layout(title = "Temperaturas diarias en 2015",
         xaxis = list(title = "D칤as"),
         yaxis = list(title = "Temperatura"))

# Muestra el gr치fico interactivo

15/11/2023, 21:36 - Emily Zavala Mi Amorcito 仇벒잺游눘: El siguiente cuadro fue realizado como un trabajo conjunto para el analisis de la abundancia de organismos identificados mediante el m칠todo de la cuadrata en ecosistemas rocosos de la playa El Pelado.

En la columna B podemos observar el nombre Comun de los organismos de flora y fauna que fueron identificados.

En la columna C, visualizamos la densidad por metro cuadrado de cada organismo descrito. Debido a que usamos una cuadra de 25 celdas, esto representa 0,25 o 1/4 de un metro cuadrado, por este motivo para determinar su densidad se multiplica la abundacia absoluta (es decir, el total de individuos por especie) por 4, de forma que tenemos 1 metro cuadrado.

En la colimna E, observamos la abundacia relativa, que no es mas que la razon entee la abundancia absoluta y la suma de las abundacias absolutas de todos los organismos.

Comparaci칩n con Otros Modelos: Para una interpretaci칩n m치s completa, tambi칠n ser칤a 칰til comparar este valor con el rendimiento de otros modelos o m칠todos de predicci칩n. Un MSE de 263 podr칤a ser considerado alto o bajo dependiendo del contexto espec칤fico y los requisitos del problema.

23/11/2023, 18:10 - Lexo: esto referente a costos de paginas web

Los costos de alojamiento web pueden variar significativamente seg칰n el proveedor, el tipo de alojamiento que elijas y la cantidad de recursos que necesites. Aqu칤 hay una descripci칩n general de los costos aproximados para diferentes opciones de alojamiento web, incluyendo un dominio y algunas medidas de seguridad:

Alojamiento compartido:

Costo aproximado: $3 a $10 USD por mes.
Este tipo de alojamiento es m치s econ칩mico, pero significa que compartes recursos del servidor con otros sitios web. Es adecuado para sitios web peque침os y de tr치fico moderado.
Alojamiento VPS (Servidor Privado Virtual):

Costo aproximado: $20 a $100 USD por mes.
Proporciona m치s recursos dedicados que el alojamiento compartido y ofrece m치s flexibilidad. Es adecuado para sitios web de tama침o mediano con tr치fico moderado a alto.
Alojamiento en la nube (por ejemplo, AWS, Google Cloud, Azure):

Costo aproximado: Puede variar significativamente seg칰n el uso y la configuraci칩n espec칤fica. Puedes usar la capa gratuita de algunos proveedores para comenzar.
Ofrece una escalabilidad excepcional y la capacidad de pagar solo por los recursos que consumes. Es adecuado para sitios web de cualquier tama침o, desde peque침os hasta grandes empresas.
Servidores dedicados:

Costo aproximado: $80 a $500 USD por mes o m치s.
Ofrece un servidor completo dedicado solo a tu sitio web. Es adecuado para sitios web grandes con tr치fico alto y requisitos de rendimiento espec칤ficos.
Dominio:

Costo aproximado: $10 a $20 USD por a침o para un dominio est치ndar.
El costo del dominio puede variar seg칰n la extensi칩n (.com, .net, .io, etc.) y el registrador de dominios que elijas.
Certificado SSL:

Costo aproximado: Puede ser gratuito o de $10 a $100 USD por a침o, dependiendo del proveedor y el tipo de certificado SSL que necesites.
Ten en cuenta que estos son solo estimados y los precios reales pueden variar. Adem치s, algunos proveedores de alojamiento web ofrecen paquetes que incluyen el registro de dominio y el certificado SSL de forma gratuita. A medida que consideres tus opciones, aseg칰rate de revisar las caracter칤sticas espec칤ficas que ofrece cada proveedor y las necesidades espec칤ficas de tu sitio web.

Recuerda que la seguridad tambi칠n es crucial. El costo de medidas de seguridad adicionales, como firewalls, servicios de monitoreo de seguridad o servicios de respaldo, tambi칠n puede influir en el presupuesto total.

1/12/2023, 20:19 - Lexo: Instructions
Each student will select a topic of ethical concern for the field. This does not necessarily have to be pure bioinformatics or data science topic, but a topic that is tied to the field is appropriate. You will write a 1 page, single-spaced (11 pt. font) report on this issue. This is not an opinion paper, rather you will provide a description of the ethical concern and cite relevant resources (e.g., scientific reporting, option pieces in the press, etc.). The style of this report should be similar to, e.g., Science News. Assume your audience is an educated non-scientist. This report will be graded as follows:
3 pts: Clear presentation of the ethical issue/concern.
2 pts: Citations included. Citations should be included in a consistent format. (Formatting 1 pt of the 2.)
1 pt: Report written such that it is accessible to the intended audience.
1 pt: Report is written well, in terms of spelling and grammar.

amor, esto es el reporte q es para el 5 de este mes, sobre etica si es relacionado a mi tema de tesis mejor

2/12/2023, 02:39 - Emily Zavala Mi Amorcito 仇벒잺游눘: To whom it may concern,

I am reaching out to you with the hope of sharing the delicate situation that has led me to seek refuge in your country to preserve my life. I am Olga Mar칤a Pilozo Cordero, passport holder A3834337, and until October 2, 2023, I worked as an executive credit assistant at Banco Pichincha in Ecuador, part of the CREDIFE Business Development team.

For several years, I have diligently worked at the bank, facilitating credit approvals, and maintaining careful attention to my personal and professional life, given the sensitive nature of my job. However, on December 12, 2023, my life took an unexpected turn when I received multiple calls from unknown numbers during my work departure time.

Although I couldn't answer those calls at that moment, I returned to work the next day, only to be approached by two polarized black vans that blocked my path. I received another call from one of the previous numbers, with clear instructions to complete a credit application in the name of Milena Zambrano, stating that it was an order given by one of the leaders of the Chone Killers. I was demanded to make the application for $70,000 and ensure its approval.

I immediately reported the incident to my boss, who requested a review of my activities and authorized an early departure for my safety. Despite this, upon returning home, I was again approached by an unmarked van, where two men threatened me, showing detailed photographs of my family and demanding that I comply with their demands. Fearing for my family's safety, we decided to move to Cuenca, considered the safest city in Ecuador.

However, while exploring the possibility of moving, we realized the extended control that this gang exercises over the country. Faced with uncertainty and recommendations from friends and family, we made the difficult decision to seek refuge outside the country, as my safety and that of my family remained at risk.

Attached to this letter, you will find supporting documents, including records of threatening calls. I hope these documents provide the necessary evidence of the imminent danger I face and support my asylum request.

I understand the gravity of my request and am willing to fully cooperate with any investigation or inquiry to verify the authenticity of my claims. My primary goal is to rebuild my life in a place where I can live free from constant fears.

I sincerely thank you for your time in considering my request. If additional information is required, please do not hesitate to contact me.

Sincerely,

Olga Mar칤a Pilozo Cordero
